hands_on_practices.problem:
A homogeneous, linear elastic, isotropic solid is in a plane state of stress on the Cartesian axes $\{x,y\}$. The Cauchy stress tensor restricted to the $\{x,y\}$-plane, written in the $\{x,y\}$ basis and using the sign convention where a positive shear stress $\tau_{xy}$ acts on the $x$-face in the $+y$ direction, is
$$
\boldsymbol{\sigma} \;=\;
\begin{pmatrix}
\sigma_{x} & \tau_{xy}\\
\tau_{xy} & \sigma_{y}
\end{pmatrix}
\;=\;
\begin{pmatrix}
120\,\mathrm{MPa} & 50\,\mathrm{MPa}\\
50\,\mathrm{MPa} & -30\,\mathrm{MPa}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Using only fundamental definitions and constructions, do the following.

1) Starting from the definition of traction and the tensorial transformation of stress under a rigid rotation of the axes, construct the two-dimensional Mohr’s circle for this stress state. Identify the circle’s center and radius from quantities that do not depend on the in-plane orientation (stress invariants under in-plane rotation), and use the geometry of the circle to determine the smallest positive rotation angle $\theta$ between the original $x$-axis and the major principal stress direction. Do not invoke any memorized transformation formulas; your reasoning must proceed from first principles and the geometry of Mohr’s construction.

2) Independently verify the same angle $\theta$ by computing the eigenvector of the Cauchy stress tensor corresponding to its largest eigenvalue (major principal stress), interpreting the eigenvector direction as the principal direction relative to the $x$-axis.

Report only the angle $\theta$ in degrees, as a single number, rounded to four significant figures. State your final numerical result in degrees. No other quantities should be reported in the final answer.
